(1493, 'Re: Violent Videogames and their effects', 'Like Alpha said, video games are not, and have never been the problem.\r\n\r\nIf someone, child, teenage or adult plays any remotely violent video game and decides to get an Uzi and climb a clock tower, It is not the video games fault. For every person who thinks like this, there is literally 1 million+ people who chooses not to.\r\n\r\nFirst off, the ESRB, PEGI, ACB, BBFC and all the other content rating companies do their jobs. They label all games according to whom should be playing it. If a kid ends up with a GTA or Saints Row or any modern FPS game It is not the game industries fault. It''s whoever bought that kid the game in the first place'' fault.\r\n\r\nAnd if they go postal over playing a video game, something was wrong with them in the first place. It it hadn''t been a video game It would have been a movie, or some music, or a book that set them off. People just want to label the cause of effect to relieve themselves of any guilt.\r\n\r\nI read that a few people were blaming Mass Effect for the recent school shooting.\r\nMass Effect is a science fiction RPG. You shoot aliens with unrealistic guns, and have psycho-kinetic abilities. Their argument is invalid. Mass Effect didn''t cause it.\r\n\r\nI could argue a lot more, but I would not be as entertaining or factual as these two guys, so please everyone who wants to discuss this further, do yourselves a huge favor and watch this.\r\n\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MaF9nbLo8as', 1488, 9, '2012-12-20 18:07:15', 46, 'yes', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 'no', '', '', ''),
