(1495, 'Re: Violent Videogames and their effects', 'That was a good video and puts to rest some theories on video games. Do I think video games are too violent? Yeah I sort of do. For example, when you see a game advertised, unless it''s an indie game, its always the violence and action that is publicized. Borderlands 2 advertised its bazillion guns, Black Ops 2 advertised ways to kill people in multiplayer, Fallout 3 and New Vegas advertised the ability to choose which body parts of enemies to blow off, and Assassins Creed advertises ways to assassinate. \r\nBut why do publishers advertise that? Why not advertise the story of the game, or the graphics of the game? Violence sells. Humans love violence. From the Romans gladiatorial matches, to dog fighting and wrestling, through out history, we found ways to enjoy violence. I''m not a scientist or neurologist so I cant tell you why we love violence, but just a quick look back at history is pretty damning evidence that we do love it.\r\nVideo games are simply something that opponents of the medium don''t understand. Violent movies were blamed for ills in the world, rock music too, and television. Anything that a generation just doesn''t understand, is deemed as evil and brainwashing. It''s just how it is. People blame what they don''t get. It''s easier to blame what you don''t get because you can place what ever ideals you have into your argument, as Jack Thompson does. A case could be made that video games are the cause in the decrease of violent crime. It is something for people to take out aggression in. When I''m mad about work or something, I''ll more than likely seek to play a few rounds of Battlefield 3 to calm down. My aggression and anger is redirected away from other people and instead on faceless enemies. It could very well be that way for others.\r\n\r\nMy final thoughts on this issue is that ultimately, the burden is on parents to decide what is right and wrong for their children. These kids don''t buy the games themselves. They either bought it with allowance money from their parents or got their parents to buy it for them. The ESRB, while is weird about the sex-violence ratio (Hyperdimension Neptunia mk.2 got an M for suggestive dialogue, and the tentacle bondage thing) it does tell you right on the back what is in the game, down to tobacco usage. Parents need to use this. If the game says Blood and Gore and is rated M, well maybe 7 year old little Timmy doesn''t need to play it. Just as a preant wouldn''t allow their kid to drive before 16, maybe parents need to not allow their kid to play a rated M game until they are older.\r\n', 1488, 16, '2012-12-20 21:13:13', 46, 'yes', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '', '', 'no', '', '', ''),
